<ArticleLayout
  title="Side Tables, Coffee Tables and Console Tables: What to Compare Before You Buy"
  description="A practical Australian guide to choosing side tables, coffee tables and console tables, including size, height, clearance, materials, renters, kids, pets and small living rooms."
  category="Living Spaces"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="10 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/living-room.webp"
  imageAlt="A warm Australian living room with a sofa, coffee table, side table and soft natural light"
>
  <p>
    Living-room tables are often chosen because they match a sofa, rug or TV unit. That can
    be a reasonable starting point, but tables affect how the room works every day. A coffee
    table that is too large can block movement. A side table that is too low can be awkward
    to reach. A console table can become a dumping zone if it has no clear job.
  </p>
  <p>
    The better starting point is to decide what the table needs to hold, where people walk,
    how the seating is arranged and whether the table will make the room easier or harder to
    live in. This matters in compact apartments, open-plan homes, family rooms, rental
    properties and shared living spaces where every surface tends to get used.
  </p>
  <p>
    This guide covers what to compare before choosing side tables, coffee tables, console
    tables, nesting tables, tray tables, sofa tables or ottomans used with trays.
  </p>

  <h2>Our Take</h2>
  <p>
    A useful living-room table should earn its place in the room. For most Australian homes,
    that means the table is the right height for the seating, leaves enough clearance,
    provides the surface or compartments the household actually uses, and can be cleaned
    without moving half the room.
  </p>
  <p>
    A larger or more decorative table is not automatically better if it interrupts walkways,
    clashes with the rug, or simply creates another place for clutter to collect. The best
    choice is usually the table that supports the room's routine without becoming another
    chore.
  </p>

  <h2>Start With What the Table Needs to Do</h2>
  <p>
    Before comparing styles, list what the table needs to hold. In some homes, a coffee table
    mainly holds drinks, snacks and remotes. In others, it becomes the place for board games,
    children's books, laptop work, pet supplies, chargers, glasses or craft items.
  </p>
  <p>
    Side tables may need to support lamps, books, phones, tissues, reading glasses and
    coasters. Console tables might act as a drop zone near an entry, a place for keys behind
    a sofa, or a visual boundary in an open-plan room. Display decor is fine if the room still
    functions, but it should not be the only reason the table exists.
  </p>
  <p>
    Function should come before style because tables collect real household items quickly.
    If the room already struggles with everyday clutter, the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-storage-ideas-everyday-australian-homes/">living room storage guide</a>{" "}
    can help you decide what needs a home before adding another surface.
  </p>

  <h2>Coffee Tables: Size, Height and Clearance</h2>
  <p>
    Coffee table height should be compared with the sofa seat height. If the table is much
    higher or lower than the seating, it may feel awkward for drinks, snacks, books or remote
    controls. Also check the distance from the sofa to the table so people can sit, stand and
    move around it comfortably.
  </p>
  <p>
    Rectangular coffee tables can suit longer sofas, but they can dominate small rooms.
    Round or oval tables may work in some tight layouts because their shape can feel softer,
    but they still need enough surface area and clearance. Square tables can suit balanced
    seating layouts, though they may feel bulky in narrow rooms.
  </p>
  <p>
    Lift-top coffee tables can add function for laptop work or casual meals, but they may add
    weight, mechanisms and clutter risk. Coffee tables with drawers or shelves can help if
    items are sorted. Check rug placement before choosing table size, especially if the table
    will sit fully on the rug.
  </p>

  <h2>Side Tables: Reach, Lamps and Everyday Items</h2>
  <p>
    A side table should suit the seat beside it. Compare the table height with the sofa arm
    or chair arm, then think about what needs to sit on the surface. A lamp, drink, phone and
    book can take up more room than expected.
  </p>
  <p>
    Narrow side tables can suit apartments and tight lounge rooms. A small drawer can hide
    remotes or glasses, while an open shelf can hold books or a small basket. C-shaped or
    sofa-side tables can be flexible, but check how stable they feel on the actual floor
    surface and whether they slide under the sofa as expected.
  </p>
  <p>
    Matching side tables are not always necessary. A reading chair may need a lamp and book
    space, while a TV seat may only need a place for a drink and remote. Side tables should
    not block recliners, curtains, sliding doors or normal movement through the room.
  </p>

  <h2>Console Tables and Sofa Tables</h2>
  <p>
    Console tables can sit behind sofas, against walls, near entries or along the edge of an
    open-plan living area. They can help define a zone and give small items a landing spot,
    but they can also narrow walkways if the depth is not checked carefully.
  </p>
  <p>
    Measure height, depth and length before buying. A console behind a sofa should make sense
    with the sofa back, nearby walkways and any lamps or chargers that may sit on top. Lower
    shelves and baskets can be useful if they have a clear purpose, but drawers can become
    clutter traps without a simple plan.
  </p>
  <p>
    Wall-adjacent furniture needs practical caution. Follow manufacturer instructions, check
    product dimensions and weight limits, and avoid overloading tabletops, shelves or
    drawers. Renters should avoid drilling or permanent changes unless approved.
  </p>

  <h2>Nesting Tables, Ottomans and Flexible Options</h2>
  <p>
    Nesting tables can work well in flexible living rooms because they can be separated when
    visitors arrive and tucked together when not needed. The risk is that they become several
    extra clutter surfaces. Before buying, think about whether they will genuinely be nested
    away.
  </p>
  <p>
    Ottomans can soften a room and work as a footrest, occasional seat or table surface when
    paired with a tray. They may not provide a firm surface on their own, and fabric surfaces
    can need more care around drinks, snacks and pet hair.
  </p>
  <p>
    Tray tables, foldable tables and lightweight occasional tables can suit renters and small
    rooms. Flexible furniture is useful only if it is easy to move, stable enough for the
    intended use and not just another piece to manage.
  </p>

  <h2>Drawers, Shelves, Open Bases and Hidden Compartments</h2>
  <p>
    Drawers can hide remotes, coasters, chargers and small devices, but they can also become
    junk drawers. Open shelves show what is stored and are easy to access, though they collect
    dust and can make a room look busier.
  </p>
  <p>
    Lower tiers can hold books, baskets or blankets if used deliberately. Hidden compartments
    can be useful for items that genuinely belong in the living room, but they can encourage
    forgotten clutter if there is no routine for clearing them.
  </p>
  <p>
    Open-base tables can make a small room feel lighter. Closed or solid tables can hide mess
    but may feel heavier visually. Decide what each compartment is for before buying, and
    avoid adding extra compartments for unsorted items.
  </p>

  <h2>Materials, Cleaning and Everyday Wear</h2>
  <p>
    Timber-look, laminate, solid timber, metal, glass, stone-look, rattan, fabric ottomans
    and painted finishes all behave differently in daily use. Glass can look light but shows
    fingerprints and dust. Dark finishes can show dust, while light finishes may show marks.
  </p>
  <p>
    Rattan and textured surfaces can collect crumbs and dust. Fabric ottomans can absorb
    spills or hold pet hair depending on the product. Timber and veneer can mark from drinks,
    heat or oils, so check care instructions before buying.
  </p>
  <p>
    Choose materials that suit how the room is actually used. A delicate finish may be fine
    in a quiet adult lounge, but a family room used for snacks, pets, games and homework may
    need something easier to wipe and maintain.
  </p>

  <h2>Small Living Rooms, Apartments and Rentals</h2>
  <p>
    Small rooms often need clearance more than extra furniture. A compact coffee table,
    narrow side table or one flexible surface may work better than a matching set. In some
    apartments, nesting tables or tray tables may offer occasional function without filling
    the room all week.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check balcony doors, sliding doors, main walkways and fixed furniture positions. A
    console table can help define an open-plan zone, but only if it does not narrow a path
    that people use every day. Lightweight furniture can be easier to move, but it still
    needs to feel stable on the floor surface.
  </p>
  <p>
    Renters may prefer freestanding tables over wall-mounted or fixed options. Avoid
    permanent changes unless approved, and seek suitable help where installation, wall fixing
    or specialist safety concerns are involved.
  </p>

  <h2>Kids, Pets and Shared Family Rooms</h2>
  <p>
    Family rooms need tables that are easy to use, easy to clean and not constantly in the
    way. Kids' toys, snacks, craft items and books can overrun a coffee table if there is no
    plan for where they go at the end of the day.
  </p>
  <p>
    Pet households should think about tails, jumping, chewing, hair and cleaning without
    expecting any table to be immune to wear. Low tables can collect clutter faster in busy
    rooms, and heavy decor may be impractical on surfaces used every day.
  </p>
  <p>
    Follow manufacturer instructions and weight limits. Keep walkways clear, avoid
    overloading tables, and secure furniture according to manufacturer guidance where
    relevant.
  </p>

  <h2>How Tables Work With Rugs, Sofas and TV Units</h2>
  <p>
    Coffee tables should work with the rug footprint, not fight it. If the table sits on a
    rug, check that the rug is large enough for the table and seating arrangement. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-rug-size-and-placement-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">living room rug size guide</a>{" "}
    covers measuring the seating zone and walkways in more detail.
  </p>
  <p>
    Side tables need to be within reach without blocking movement. Console tables can sit
    behind sofas in open-plan rooms, but walkway clearance still matters. A table that looks
    balanced from one angle may be frustrating if it narrows the path to the kitchen, balcony
    or hallway.
  </p>
  <p>
    TV units and coffee tables should not compete for floor space. If the media area is tight,
    check the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/tv-unit-and-media-storage-what-to-measure-before-you-buy/">TV unit and media storage guide</a>{" "}
    alongside table measurements so drawers, cupboards, cables and walkways still work.
  </p>

  <h2>Trade-Offs Worth Knowing</h2>
  <p>
    A large coffee table gives more surface area, but it can reduce walkway clearance. A
    small coffee table keeps the room open, but it may not hold what the household uses every
    day. Round tables can soften a tight layout, but they may offer less rectangular surface
    area for books, trays or board games.
  </p>
  <p>
    Glass can make a room feel lighter but shows fingerprints. Drawers hide small items but
    can become junk drawers. Open shelves keep items visible but can look busy. Nesting
    tables add flexibility but create more pieces to manage.
  </p>
  <p>
    Console tables can define a zone but narrow walkways. Ottoman tables can soften a room
    but may need a tray for a firmer surface. Decorative styling can look warm, but everyday
    function should decide whether the table deserves the space.
  </p>

  <h2>Before You Buy Checklist</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Decide what the table needs to hold.</li>
    <li>Measure the sofa and seating area.</li>
    <li>Measure walkway clearance around the table.</li>
    <li>Check coffee table distance from the sofa.</li>
    <li>Check side table height against sofa or chair arms.</li>
    <li>Check rug size and placement.</li>
    <li>Check TV unit and media area clearance.</li>
    <li>Check doors, sliding doors and balcony access.</li>
    <li>Decide whether drawers, shelves or a simple surface are actually needed.</li>
    <li>Check product dimensions and manufacturer instructions.</li>
    <li>Check weight limits.</li>
    <li>Choose materials that suit cleaning and everyday wear.</li>
    <li>Avoid overloading surfaces, drawers or shelves.</li>
    <li>Keep liquids away from electrical items.</li>
    <li>Avoid permanent changes in rentals unless approved.</li>
    <li>Do not buy a table only because it matches a styled photo.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Buying a coffee table that is too large for the walkway.</li>
    <li>Choosing a side table that is too low or too high for the sofa.</li>
    <li>Forgetting rug placement.</li>
    <li>Blocking sliding doors or balcony access.</li>
    <li>Buying drawers without a plan for what goes inside.</li>
    <li>Choosing glass or glossy finishes without accepting cleaning needs.</li>
    <li>Adding a console table where the walkway is already narrow.</li>
    <li>Buying nesting tables that will never be nested away.</li>
    <li>Treating tables as general clutter drop zones.</li>
    <li>Choosing matching tables when each seat has different needs.</li>
    <li>Ignoring pets, kids and everyday cleaning.</li>
    <li>Buying before measuring the actual seating area.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Suitability-Based Product Angles</h2>
  <p>
    For small living rooms, a compact coffee table or nesting tables may be worth considering
    if walkway clearance is tight. For renters, freestanding side tables and consoles are
    usually simpler than fixed or wall-mounted options.
  </p>
  <p>
    For family rooms, easy-clean surfaces and practical compartments may matter more than
    delicate finishes. For pet households, lower-maintenance surfaces and fewer fragile
    decorative pieces may be more realistic. For closed compartments, drawers can hide remotes
    and small items if they are not treated as junk drawers.
  </p>
  <p>
    For flexible layouts, nesting tables or tray tables may suit occasional use if they can
    be moved easily. For open-plan spaces, a console table can help define a zone if it does
    not block movement. For low-maintenance rooms, fewer tables with clearer purposes may
    work better than several decorative pieces.
  </p>

  <h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
  <p>
    Living-room tables should be chosen around the way the room is used. The right coffee
    table, side table or console table should fit the seating area, leave room to move, hold
    the items that genuinely need a surface, and avoid becoming another clutter point.
  </p>
  <p>
    A simple, well-measured table that suits daily use will usually serve the household
    better than a larger or more decorative piece chosen mainly for appearance. Measure the
    seating area, check the rug and walkways, then choose the table that makes the room easier
    to live in.
  </p>

